  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Fastify Framework Patterns</title>
    <summary>Fastify is a modern web framework for Node.js that prioritizes performance, TypeScript support, and comprehensive schema validation using JSON Schema and TypeBox. Features a plugin architecture, built-in security, rate limiting, CORS, graceful shutdown, and custom error handling.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Fastify solves performance bottlenecks and type safety challenges in Node.js APIs. Its plugin architecture enables modular, composable applications. TypeBox integration provides type-safe schemas that triple as request validators, response serializers, and OpenAPI documentation. The framework ships security-first with helmet, rate limiting, and CORS as first-class plugins. Schema-driven serialization is measurably faster than hand-coded JSON stringification.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Performance-critical APIs where high RPS and fast serialization matter.</item>
        <item>TypeScript-first projects requiring strict type safety and schema validation.</item>
        <item>Greenfield HTTP APIs with JSON payloads and microservices architectures.</item>
        <item>Migrating Express 4/5 services that have outgrown ad-hoc validation.</item>
        <item>Building secure-by-default services where helmet, rate limiting, JWT, and CORS are required.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Edge-runtime targets (Cloudflare Workers, Vercel Edge) — use Hono or Itty Router instead; Fastify is Node-native only.</item>
        <item>Static-site or thin SSR layers — use Next.js, SvelteKit, or similar frameworks that own the HTTP layer.</item>
        <item>WebSocket-heavy realtime applications — Socket.IO or uWebSockets.js may suit better despite Fastify's @fastify/websocket plugin.</item>
        <item>Trivial scripts and CLIs — Fastify boot weight exceeds value for minimal utilities.</item>
        <item>Bun-only services without specific Fastify plugins — use Bun.serve with Hono for lighter footprint.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="key-principles">
      <p>Fastify applications are built on five core principles:</p>
      <rules>
        <rule>
          <statement>Plugin architecture: decompose applications into reusable, composable plugins registered via await app.register().</statement>
          <rationale>Plugins enable modular code, decoupling concerns, and reuse across projects. Prevents monolithic route files.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Schema validation: define request and response shapes using TypeBox or JSON Schema for every route.</statement>
          <rationale>Schema-driven validation catches bad inputs early, prevents silent data corruption, and auto-generates OpenAPI docs and type hints.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>TypeScript-first: use TypeBox to generate types from schemas, avoiding hand-written types that drift from validators.</statement>
          <rationale>Single source of truth for both validation and types prevents the classic bug where types and validators diverge.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>High throughput: leverage fast-json-stringify (built-in serializer) and async/await for non-blocking I/O.</statement>
          <rationale>Fastify benchmarks at 2–3× higher RPS than Express on identical workloads.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Graceful shutdown: use close-with-grace or app.close() hooks to drain in-flight requests before terminating.</statement>
          <rationale>Prevents dropped connections, incomplete transactions, and zero-downtime deployments.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </rules>
    </section>
    <section name="fastify-application-setup">
      <p>Initialize Fastify with TypeBox type provider, register plugins, define error handler, and wire routes.</p>
      <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
// app.ts
import Fastify, { FastifyInstance } from 'fastify';
import cors from '@fastify/cors';
import helmet from '@fastify/helmet';
import rateLimit from '@fastify/rate-limit';
import { TypeBoxTypeProvider } from '@fastify/type-provider-typebox';
import { userRoutes } from './routes/users.routes';
import { authRoutes } from './routes/auth.routes';
import { errorHandler } from './plugins/errorHandler';
import { config } from './config';

export async function createApp(): Promise<FastifyInstance> {
  const app = Fastify({
    logger: {
      level: config.logLevel,
      transport: config.isDevelopment
        ? { target: 'pino-pretty' }
        : undefined,
    },
  }).withTypeProvider<TypeBoxTypeProvider>();

  // Plugins
  await app.register(helmet);
  await app.register(cors, {
    origin: config.corsOrigins,
    credentials: true,
  });
  await app.register(rateLimit, {
    max: 100,
    timeWindow: '15 minutes',
  });

  // Custom error handler
  app.setErrorHandler(errorHandler);

  // Health check
  app.get('/health', async () => ({
    status: 'ok',
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
  }));

  // Routes
  await app.register(authRoutes, { prefix: '/api/v1/auth' });
  await app.register(userRoutes, { prefix: '/api/v1/users' });

  return app;
}

// server.ts
import { createApp } from './app';
import { config } from './config';

async function start() {
  const app = await createApp();

  try {
    await app.listen({ port: config.port, host: '0.0.0.0' });
  } catch (err) {
    app.log.error(err);
    process.exit(1);
  }
}

start();
]]></code>
      <note>Always use withTypeProvider&lt;TypeBoxTypeProvider&gt;() to enable type-safe routes and schemas. Pino logger requires pino-pretty transport in development for readable output.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="routes-with-typebox">
      <p>Define routes with request and response schemas. TypeBox Type.Object() generates types compatible with FastifyRequest and reply.</p>
      <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
// routes/users.routes.ts
import { FastifyPluginAsync } from 'fastify';
import { Type, Static } from '@sinclair/typebox';

const UserSchema = Type.Object({
  id: Type.String(),
  email: Type.String({ format: 'email' }),
  name: Type.String(),
  createdAt: Type.String({ format: 'date-time' }),
});

const CreateUserSchema = Type.Object({
  email: Type.String({ format: 'email' }),
  name: Type.String({ minLength: 1, maxLength: 100 }),
  password: Type.String({ minLength: 8 }),
});

const UpdateUserSchema = Type.Partial(
  Type.Object({
    email: Type.String({ format: 'email' }),
    name: Type.String({ minLength: 1, maxLength: 100 }),
  })
);

const ParamsSchema = Type.Object({
  id: Type.String(),
});

const QuerySchema = Type.Object({
  page: Type.Optional(Type.Number({ minimum: 1, default: 1 })),
  limit: Type.Optional(Type.Number({ minimum: 1, maximum: 100, default: 20 })),
  search: Type.Optional(Type.String()),
});

type User = Static<typeof UserSchema>;
type CreateUser = Static<typeof CreateUserSchema>;
type UpdateUser = Static<typeof UpdateUserSchema>;

export const userRoutes: FastifyPluginAsync = async (app) => {
  // GET /users
  app.get<{
    Querystring: Static<typeof QuerySchema>;
    Reply: { users: User[]; total: number; page: number; limit: number };
  }>(
    '/',
    {
      schema: {
        querystring: QuerySchema,
        response: {
          200: Type.Object({
            users: Type.Array(UserSchema),
            total: Type.Number(),
            page: Type.Number(),
            limit: Type.Number(),
          }),
        },
      },
      preHandler: [app.authenticate],
    },
    async (request, reply) => {
      const { page = 1, limit = 20, search } = request.query;
      const result = await app.userService.getUsers(page, limit, search);
      return result;
    }
  );

  // GET /users/:id
  app.get<{
    Params: Static<typeof ParamsSchema>;
    Reply: { data: User };
  }>(
    '/:id',
    {
      schema: {
        params: ParamsSchema,
        response: {
          200: Type.Object({ data: UserSchema }),
        },
      },
      preHandler: [app.authenticate],
    },
    async (request) => {
      const user = await app.userService.getUser(request.params.id);
      return { data: user };
    }
  );

  // POST /users
  app.post<{
    Body: CreateUser;
    Reply: { data: User };
  }>(
    '/',
    {
      schema: {
        body: CreateUserSchema,
        response: {
          201: Type.Object({ data: UserSchema }),
        },
      },
    },
    async (request, reply) => {
      const user = await app.userService.createUser(request.body);
      reply.status(201);
      return { data: user };
    }
  );

  // PATCH /users/:id
  app.patch<{
    Params: Static<typeof ParamsSchema>;
    Body: UpdateUser;
    Reply: { data: User };
  }>(
    '/:id',
    {
      schema: {
        params: ParamsSchema,
        body: UpdateUserSchema,
        response: {
          200: Type.Object({ data: UserSchema }),
        },
      },
      preHandler: [app.authenticate],
    },
    async (request) => {
      const user = await app.userService.updateUser(
        request.params.id,
        request.body
      );
      return { data: user };
    }
  );

  // DELETE /users/:id
  app.delete<{
    Params: Static<typeof ParamsSchema>;
  }>(
    '/:id',
    {
      schema: {
        params: ParamsSchema,
        response: {
          204: Type.Null(),
        },
      },
      preHandler: [app.authenticate],
    },
    async (request, reply) => {
      await app.userService.deleteUser(request.params.id);
      reply.status(204).send();
    }
  );
};
]]></code>
      <note>Use Type.Object() to define schemas; then Static&lt;typeof Schema&gt; extracts TypeScript types. Every route MUST have request (body, params, querystring) and response schemas. Use Type.Optional() and Type.Partial() for optional fields.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="authentication-plugin">
      <p>Create a reusable JWT authentication plugin using fastify-plugin (fp) to decorate the app instance.</p>
      <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
// plugins/auth.ts
import { FastifyPluginAsync, FastifyRequest } from 'fastify';
import fp from 'fastify-plugin';
import jwt from 'jsonwebtoken';

declare module 'fastify' {
  interface FastifyInstance {
    authenticate: (request: FastifyRequest) => Promise<void>;
  }
  interface FastifyRequest {
    user: { userId: string; email: string };
  }
}

const authPlugin: FastifyPluginAsync = async (app) => {
  app.decorate('authenticate', async (request: FastifyRequest) => {
    const authHeader = request.headers.authorization;

    if (!authHeader?.startsWith('Bearer ')) {
      throw app.httpErrors.unauthorized('Missing authorization');
    }

    try {
      const token = authHeader.slice(7);
      const payload = jwt.verify(token, app.config.jwtSecret);
      request.user = payload as { userId: string; email: string };
    } catch {
      throw app.httpErrors.unauthorized('Invalid token');
    }
  });
};

export default fp(authPlugin, { name: 'auth' });
]]></code>
      <note>CRITICAL: use fastify-plugin (fp) to break encapsulation. Without fp(), decorators like app.authenticate are scoped to the plugin and invisible to routes. Always declare module augmentation for custom decorators and request properties.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="database-plugin">
      <p>Decorate Fastify with a database connection pool, initialize on plugin load, and clean up on shutdown.</p>
      <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
// plugins/database.ts
import { FastifyPluginAsync } from 'fastify';
import fp from 'fastify-plugin';
import { Pool } from 'pg';

declare module 'fastify' {
  interface FastifyInstance {
    db: Pool;
  }
}

const databasePlugin: FastifyPluginAsync = async (app) => {
  const pool = new Pool({
    host: app.config.dbHost,
    port: app.config.dbPort,
    database: app.config.dbName,
    user: app.config.dbUser,
    password: app.config.dbPassword,
  });

  // Test connection
  await pool.query('SELECT 1');
  app.log.info('Database connected');

  // Decorate instance with pool
  app.decorate('db', pool);

  // Close pool on shutdown
  app.addHook('onClose', async (instance) => {
    await instance.db.end();
    instance.log.info('Database connection closed');
  });
};

export default fp(databasePlugin, { name: 'database' });
]]></code>
      <note>Test the connection immediately to catch configuration errors early. Use app.addHook('onClose', ...) for cleanup to ensure graceful shutdown. Always use fp() for plugins that decorate the app.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="error-handler-plugin">
      <p>Centralized error handler returning RFC 7807 Problem Details format, handling validation errors, HTTP errors, and unexpected exceptions.</p>
      <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
// plugins/errorHandler.ts
import { FastifyError, FastifyReply, FastifyRequest } from 'fastify';

export function errorHandler(
  error: FastifyError,
  request: FastifyRequest,
  reply: FastifyReply
) {
  request.log.error(error);

  // Validation errors
  if (error.validation) {
    return reply.status(400).send({
      error: 'Validation Error',
      message: error.message,
      details: error.validation,
    });
  }

  // HTTP errors
  if (error.statusCode) {
    return reply.status(error.statusCode).send({
      error: error.name,
      message: error.message,
    });
  }

  // Unknown errors
  return reply.status(500).send({
    error: 'Internal Server Error',
    message: 'An unexpected error occurred',
  });
}
]]></code>
      <note>Always return structured error responses. Validation errors include the validation details array. Never expose internal error messages to clients in production.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Not awaiting plugin registration. Registering plugins without await causes async race conditions where plugins are only partially loaded when routes run.</description>
        <reason>Without await, the plugin's registration hooks may not complete before the app tries to use decorated properties or config, leading to undefined references and runtime crashes.</reason>
        <example type="bad">
          <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
export async function createApp() {
  const app = Fastify();
  app.register(cors); // Missing await
  app.register(helmet); // Missing await
  return app;
}
]]></code>
        </example>
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
export async function createApp() {
  const app = Fastify();
  await app.register(cors);
  await app.register(helmet);
  return app;
}
]]></code>
        </example>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Missing type safety in routes. Omitting TypeBox schemas or using inline plain objects without Type.Object() leads to loose inference and broken handler typing.</description>
        <reason>TypeScript cannot infer request/reply types without explicit schemas, causing unsafe property access and runtime errors. Loose types bypass validation.</reason>
        <example type="bad">
          <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
app.get('/users/:id', async (request, reply) => {
  const id = request.params.id; // any type
  const user = await getUser(id);
  return user;
});
]]></code>
        </example>
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
app.get<{
  Params: { id: string };
  Reply: { data: User };
}>(
  '/:id',
  {
    schema: {
      params: Type.Object({ id: Type.String() }),
      response: {
        200: Type.Object({ data: UserSchema }),
      },
    },
  },
  async (request) => {
    const id = request.params.id; // string type
    const user = await getUser(id);
    return { data: user };
  }
);
]]></code>
        </example>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Mixing reply.send() and return statements. Using both in the same handler causes double-response errors where Fastify tries to send the response twice.</description>
        <reason>Fastify's handler can return a value OR call reply.send(), not both. Mixing them violates the implicit contract and crashes with ERR_HTTP_HEADERS_SENT.</reason>
        <example type="bad">
          <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
app.post('/users', async (request, reply) => {
  const user = await createUser(request.body);
  reply.send(user); // Inconsistent: some use return, some use send
});
]]></code>
        </example>
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
app.post('/users', async (request, reply) => {
  const user = await createUser(request.body);
  reply.status(201);
  return { data: user }; // Always return, use reply for status only
});
]]></code>
        </example>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Forgetting fastify-plugin (fp) wrapper on plugins that decorate the app. Without fp, decorators are scoped to the plugin and invisible to routes.</description>
        <reason>Fastify plugins are scoped by default to prevent namespace pollution. The fp() wrapper explicitly breaks encapsulation so decorators are available app-wide. Without it, app.db or app.authenticate are undefined in routes.</reason>
        <example type="bad">
          <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
const databasePlugin: FastifyPluginAsync = async (app) => {
  const pool = new Pool({ ... });
  app.decorate('db', pool); // Scoped; routes can't access app.db
};

export default databasePlugin; // Missing fp() wrapper
]]></code>
        </example>
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
const databasePlugin: FastifyPluginAsync = async (app) => {
  const pool = new Pool({ ... });
  app.decorate('db', pool);
};

export default fp(databasePlugin, { name: 'database' }); // Wrapped in fp()
]]></code>
        </example>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="graceful-shutdown">
      <p>Use close-with-grace or Fastify's app.close() hooks to drain in-flight requests before terminating, enabling zero-downtime deployments.</p>
      <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
// server.ts (graceful shutdown excerpt)
import closeWithGrace from 'close-with-grace';
import { createApp } from './app';

const app = await createApp();
await app.listen({ port: Number(process.env.PORT ?? 3000), host: '0.0.0.0' });

closeWithGrace({ delay: 10_000 }, async ({ signal, err }) => {
  if (err) app.log.error({ err }, 'shutdown error');
  app.log.info({ signal }, 'shutting down');
  await app.close();
});
]]></code>
      <note>The delay parameter (10 seconds) gives in-flight requests time to complete before hard shutdown. This prevents dropped connections and lost transactions during deploys.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="testing">
      <p>Use app.inject() for tests instead of binding a real port. This is faster, deterministic, and safe for parallel test execution.</p>
      <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
import { test, expect } from 'vitest';
import { createApp } from '../src/app';

test('GET /health', async () => {
  const app = await createApp();
  const res = await app.inject({ method: 'GET', url: '/health' });
  expect(res.statusCode).toBe(200);
  expect(res.json()).toMatchObject({ status: 'ok' });
  await app.close();
});
]]></code>
      <note>app.inject() simulates HTTP requests without binding to a port. Use with vitest for fast, parallel-safe tests. Always call app.close() for cleanup.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <rules>
        <rule>
          <statement>Always set both request AND response schemas on every route. Response schema doubles as serializer and OpenAPI documentation source.</statement>
          <rationale>Complete schemas enable validation, serialization optimization, and auto-generated API docs. Incomplete schemas hide fields in responses.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Plugins that decorate app must be wrapped in fastify-plugin (fp) to break encapsulation and make decorators app-wide.</statement>
          <rationale>Without fp, decorators are plugin-scoped and routes cannot access them. Silent runtime failures ensue.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Always await app.register(...) — forgetting await causes async plugins to half-load and race conditions follow.</statement>
          <rationale>Async plugin registration is required for proper initialization and hook execution order.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Error handler returns RFC 7807 Problem Details (type, title, status, detail, instance) for consistency with API consumers and OpenAPI.</statement>
          <rationale>Standardized error format improves client error handling and debuggability.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>For authentication, prefer @fastify/jwt + a verify hook on protected route prefixes; never decode JWT manually.</statement>
          <rationale>Centralized JWT verification prevents key rotation bugs and token tampering.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Log everything with request-bound request.log or reply.log; never use console.log in production code.</statement>
          <rationale>request.log captures request context (correlation ID, method, path, duration) for debugging. console.log is lost.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Use app.inject() for tests over starting a real port — fast, deterministic, parallel-safe.</statement>
          <rationale>Real port binding is slow and thread-unsafe. app.inject() simulates HTTP without a port.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </rules>
    </section>
    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>Recommended tools for Fastify development and deployment:</p>
      <list>
        <item>fastify-cli: Scaffold and run apps via start.js convention; `npm i -D fastify-cli`.</item>
        <item>tsx / tsdown: Dev and build tooling for TypeScript Fastify apps; tsx.is.</item>
        <item>pino-pretty: Pretty-print development logs; `npm i -D pino-pretty`.</item>
        <item>@fastify/swagger + swagger-ui: Auto-generate OpenAPI docs from JSON Schema; github.com/fastify/fastify-swagger.</item>
        <item>autocannon: Load testing and HTTP benchmarking; `npx autocannon`.</item>
        <item>clinic.js: Production diagnostics (doctor, flame, bubbleprof); clinicjs.org.</item>
        <item>@types/node + typescript: TypeScript toolchain for type checking.</item>
        <item>vitest + light-my-request (app.inject): Fast unit tests without a port; vitest.dev.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
